<subSubSection lastPageId="4" lastPageNumber="281" pageId="2" pageNumber="279" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="2.[199,1437,1979,2042]" lastBlockId="3.[151,1437,151,573]" lastPageId="3" lastPageNumber="280" pageId="2" pageNumber="279">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,345,1979,2005]" pageId="2" pageNumber="279">Description.</emphasis>
Male (
<figureCitation box="[424,517,1979,2005]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[152,255,1909,1933]" captionTargetBox="[151,1424,458,1874]" captionTargetId="figure-150@2.[151,1436,450,1883]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Habitus of Hexarhopalus (H) liuyixiaoi sp. nov. A. Male; B. Female." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4440918" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4440918/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="279">Figs 1A</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[529,543,1979,2005]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1653,1677]" captionTargetBox="[162,1431,601,1625]" captionTargetId="figure-206@3.[151,1436,597,1630]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. Diagnostic features of Hexarhopalus (H.) liuyixiaoi sp. nov. (A–G. Male; H–I. Female). A. Head and pronotum, in dorsal view; B. Antenna; C. Aedeagus, ventral view; D. Same, lateral view; E. Same, dorsal view; F. Abdominal ventrite VIII of male; G. Spiculum gastrale; H. Ventrite VIII of female and spiculum; I. Ovipositor." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4440922" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4440922/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="279">2</figureCitation>
A–G). Body more slender than female, long oval, convex, black dull-shiny. Head (
<figureCitation box="[277,369,2015,2041]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1653,1677]" captionTargetBox="[162,1431,601,1625]" captionTargetId="figure-206@3.[151,1436,597,1630]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. Diagnostic features of Hexarhopalus (H.) liuyixiaoi sp. nov. (A–G. Male; H–I. Female). A. Head and pronotum, in dorsal view; B. Antenna; C. Aedeagus, ventral view; D. Same, lateral view; E. Same, dorsal view; F. Abdominal ventrite VIII of male; G. Spiculum gastrale; H. Ventrite VIII of female and spiculum; I. Ovipositor." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4440922" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4440922/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="279">Fig. 2A</figureCitation>
) transverse. Vertex finely covered with small punctures and short hairs. Genae and clypeus covered with denser punctures and hairs. Labrum narrower than clypeus, covered with bristles of medium length in apical portion. Antennal tubercles slightly prominent, antenna (
<figureCitation box="[906,994,187,213]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1653,1677]" captionTargetBox="[162,1431,601,1625]" captionTargetId="figure-206@3.[151,1436,597,1630]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. Diagnostic features of Hexarhopalus (H.) liuyixiaoi sp. nov. (A–G. Male; H–I. Female). A. Head and pronotum, in dorsal view; B. Antenna; C. Aedeagus, ventral view; D. Same, lateral view; E. Same, dorsal view; F. Abdominal ventrite VIII of male; G. Spiculum gastrale; H. Ventrite VIII of female and spiculum; I. Ovipositor." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4440922" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4440922/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="280">Fig. 2B</figureCitation>
) nearly as long as head and pronotum combined, club loosely formed by apical four antennomeres. Antennomere I slightly expanded; II shortest, about as long as wide; III longest, more than three times as II, IV-VII similar, shorter than II, apical four dark brown, longer than wide, XI with rounded apex.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,151,573]" pageId="3" pageNumber="280">
Pronotum (
<figureCitation box="[324,411,331,357]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1653,1677]" captionTargetBox="[162,1431,601,1625]" captionTargetId="figure-206@3.[151,1436,597,1630]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. Diagnostic features of Hexarhopalus (H.) liuyixiaoi sp. nov. (A–G. Male; H–I. Female). A. Head and pronotum, in dorsal view; B. Antenna; C. Aedeagus, ventral view; D. Same, lateral view; E. Same, dorsal view; F. Abdominal ventrite VIII of male; G. Spiculum gastrale; H. Ventrite VIII of female and spiculum; I. Ovipositor." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4440922" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4440922/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="280">Fig. 2A</figureCitation>
) slightly wider than long, widest near middle, dorsal surface finely covered with small punctures and short hairs. Margins of pronotum with deep groove around, groove W-shaped on anterior part. Middle suture shallow, broadened at base, with pair of obvious depressions in middle area on both sides of the median line.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,151,573]" pageId="3" pageNumber="280">Elytra ovoid, nearly twice as long as wide, shoulders strongly narrowed, widest at apical 1/3, disc with regular rows of strongly foveolate punctures, scutellum transverse, near triangular. Hind wings completely reduced.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,151,573]" pageId="3" pageNumber="280">Femora obviously claviform at middle, all tibiae covered with brown setae at apex, protibiae and mesotibiae slightly curved, metatibiae straight.</paragraph>
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4440922" ID-Zenodo-Dep="4440922" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4440922/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="280" startId="3.[151,250,1653,1677]" targetBox="[162,1431,601,1625]" targetPageId="3">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,1653,1750]" pageId="3" pageNumber="280">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,275,1653,1677]" pageId="3" pageNumber="280">FIGURE 2.</emphasis>
Diagnostic features of 
<taxonomicName authority="Jiang &amp; Bai &amp; Ren &amp; Yang &amp; Wang, 2020" authorityName="Jiang &amp; Bai &amp; Ren &amp; Yang &amp; Wang" authorityYear="2020" box="[510,802,1654,1678]" class="Insecta" family="Tenebrionidae" genus="Hexarhopalus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="280" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="liuyixiaoi" status="sp. nov." subGenus="Hexarhopalus">
<emphasis box="[510,653,1654,1678]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="280">Hexarhopalus</emphasis>
(
<emphasis box="[667,693,1654,1677]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="280">H.</emphasis>
) 
<emphasis box="[706,802,1654,1678]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="280">liuyixiaoi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[808,886,1654,1677]" pageId="3" pageNumber="280" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
(A–G. Male; H–I. Female). 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1173,1198,1653,1677]" pageId="3" pageNumber="280">A.</emphasis>
Head and pronotum, in dorsal view; 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[283,306,1690,1714]" pageId="3" pageNumber="280">B.</emphasis>
Antenna; 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[412,436,1689,1713]" pageId="3" pageNumber="280">C.</emphasis>
Aedeagus, ventral view; 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[696,721,1690,1714]" pageId="3" pageNumber="280">D.</emphasis>
Same, lateral view; 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[931,954,1690,1714]" pageId="3" pageNumber="280">E.</emphasis>
Same, dorsal view; 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1163,1182,1690,1714]" pageId="3" pageNumber="280">F.</emphasis>
Abdominal ventrite VIII of male; 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[241,267,1725,1749]" pageId="3" pageNumber="280">G.</emphasis>
Spiculum gastrale; 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[469,495,1726,1750]" pageId="3" pageNumber="280">H.</emphasis>
Ventrite VIII of female and spiculum; 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[889,905,1726,1750]" pageId="3" pageNumber="280">I.</emphasis>
Ovipositor.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,1796,2038]" pageId="3" pageNumber="280">
Aedeagus (
<figureCitation box="[324,393,1796,1822]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1653,1677]" captionTargetBox="[162,1431,601,1625]" captionTargetId="figure-206@3.[151,1436,597,1630]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. Diagnostic features of Hexarhopalus (H.) liuyixiaoi sp. nov. (A–G. Male; H–I. Female). A. Head and pronotum, in dorsal view; B. Antenna; C. Aedeagus, ventral view; D. Same, lateral view; E. Same, dorsal view; F. Abdominal ventrite VIII of male; G. Spiculum gastrale; H. Ventrite VIII of female and spiculum; I. Ovipositor." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4440922" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4440922/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="280">Figs 2</figureCitation>
C–E) nearly symmetrical. Abdominal ventrite VIII (
<figureCitation box="[973,1056,1796,1822]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1653,1677]" captionTargetBox="[162,1431,601,1625]" captionTargetId="figure-206@3.[151,1436,597,1630]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. Diagnostic features of Hexarhopalus (H.) liuyixiaoi sp. nov. (A–G. Male; H–I. Female). A. Head and pronotum, in dorsal view; B. Antenna; C. Aedeagus, ventral view; D. Same, lateral view; E. Same, dorsal view; F. Abdominal ventrite VIII of male; G. Spiculum gastrale; H. Ventrite VIII of female and spiculum; I. Ovipositor." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4440922" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4440922/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="280">Fig. 2F</figureCitation>
) deeply split medially at posterior margin and with long dense hairs. Spiculum gastrale (
<figureCitation box="[754,841,1832,1858]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1653,1677]" captionTargetBox="[162,1431,601,1625]" captionTargetId="figure-206@3.[151,1436,597,1630]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. Diagnostic features of Hexarhopalus (H.) liuyixiaoi sp. nov. (A–G. Male; H–I. Female). A. Head and pronotum, in dorsal view; B. Antenna; C. Aedeagus, ventral view; D. Same, lateral view; E. Same, dorsal view; F. Abdominal ventrite VIII of male; G. Spiculum gastrale; H. Ventrite VIII of female and spiculum; I. Ovipositor." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4440922" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4440922/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="280">Fig. 2G</figureCitation>
) dissymmetrical, short, with large apical lobes.
</paragraph>
